/LIF R/NME R/US </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday DAVID YURMNA HOW TO WEAR MEN'S JEWELRY MEN'S BRACELET MEN'S JEWELRY MEN'S NECKLACE MEN'S RING NATIVE AMERICAN JEWELRY PEYOTE BIRD SHOULD I WEAR MEN'S JEWELRY SIDNEY GARBER STACK WHAT IS A STACK SB109611123925106337025045841038222017255001 SYND CODES_REVIEWED Fashion </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OLEM OLSF </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Life</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">How Men Can Wear Jewelry Without Looking Like Johnny Depp; You might not be ready to take a 'jewelfie' of your 'stack' of bracelets, but more guys are sporting discreet signet rings and subtle chains, too.</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>AMANDA Alexander's family has been in the jewelry business in Santa Fe, N.M., for 44 years, employing artisans to create Native-American-inspired pieces for women. Growing up, Ms. Alexander's brother and male friends didn't get why anyone would wear jewelry: "They would be like, 'We don't understand it, what's it all about?'" Still, three years ago, when Ms. Alexander joined Peyote Bird, the company her father founded, she decided to launch a men's jewelry collection, seeing an opportunity. Today, it's Peyote Bird's fastest-growing category.</Para><Para>A lot of men share Ms. Alexander's brother's fear of adornment. You won't find many guy jewelry role models: At one extreme, you've got Mr. Normal with his wedding band and watch (totally acceptable); at the other, you have Mr. T., who appears to have vomited gold chains (generally unacceptable). Tread much beyond Mr. Normal territory, most men assume, and you risk looking like you raided your mother's jewelry box.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>You may want to rethink that assumption: A happy medium is finding its way into the average man's sartorial quiver. Stroll into a department store like Barneys New York and you'll find a men-specific case to accommodate the growing number of male baubles that brands are turning out. Scroll through Instagram and you'll see hundreds of thousands of photos tagged "#mensjewelry," many featuring trendy "stacks" of multiple bracelets.</Para><Para>More men are tucking a bracelet under their shirt cuff as they realize that, like a watch, jewelry is a keepsake, an object that can trigger a memory (that time you drank too much prosecco in Italy) or mark a milestone (that time you got to be one of only 15 vice-presidents). That's why jewelry has value beyond its material worth for Anton Anger, 27, the director of product design and development at RW Guild, a Manhattan home goods store, who has been collecting silver and turquoise jewelry for over a decade. There's a reason, he said, why momentous events like your high school graduation or a Super Bowl victory are commemorated with a ring.</Para><Para>It's also true that jewelry is often more distinctive than a Rolex or a Panerai (and can be more affordable). Whether you're wearing a vintage sterling silver Navajo ring from Shiprock in Santa Fe, N.M., a dime-size signet ring from Givenchy or one of Sidney Garber's stretchy steel bracelets, jewelry can lend character to your outfit. And it's a surefire conversation-starter.</Para><Para>"I usually try to collect pieces that accent whatever I'm wearing," said Josue Julio, 31, a model in Los Angeles. For everyday wear, he'll go for thin, minimalist gold or bronze pieces that won't feel too heavy worn with a breezy T-shirt and jeans. Whenever friends or strangers spy Mr. Julio's accessories and ask for advice on buying their own jewelry, he typically says "start simple." Jewelry is usually an investment and you're apt to get more ROI out of understated pieces you can wear often.</Para><Para>Wesley Scott, 24, a designer at New York denim label 3sixteen, said that his jewelry "seems like a part of [him] at this point." No matter what else he's wearing, his daily array of three rings, a cuff and a necklace remains the same. While his shirts last only a year (if he's lucky), jewelry is a constant that endures, perhaps the most "personal" part of his personal style.</Para><Para>Mr. Scott has a particular regard for vintage Native American jewelry, which often features intricate engravings that reward close inspection (thunderbirds, clouds and arrows are common motifs), and a rich, masculine patina that tones down the flash. "I don't want to look like the rings are wearing me," he said.</Para><Para>JEWELS MAKE THE MAN // Three Ways To Wear Bling So It Doesn't Wear You</Para><Para>Bracelets in artful shapes, like an unexpected feather cuff, add quiet panache to your style.</Para><Para>Chunky but distinguished rings are discreetly manly. Updated signets are especially smart.</Para><Para>No gaudy Mr. T bling here: Elegant and understated chains are easy to wear.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Jacob Gallagher </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-mens-jewelry-trend-way-beyond-the-wedding-band-1521730307" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

